Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel offices in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Car Tourist.
At the time, the travel offices sold mainly travels to the Socialist Eastern blocs, in the West only selected at that time.
And so Czech tourists travel to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotchi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when they were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a protest course and therefore the travels to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries of the Eastern bloc (so also the Czechoslovaks).
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Since then, the travel offices also offered trips to the west, but had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel office, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
And so the thing hasn't been going on for a long time.
The so-called currency issue - the condition for an exit to the West - was only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without currency usage it would have been impossible to drive the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holiday in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekly houses and dots - a habit that continues to this day.
The current revolution of 1989 followed a re-evolution of the Czechs on foot.
While by 1989 a holiday in the DDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A powerful paradox, which you no longer realize today, is the fact that you could not travel in the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation has been lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, leading to a strong wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough time from their trip to the West, each wanted to be there for at least a few days.
This is how the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in Paris in the park, since at the time, they had the money for a stay in the hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature of foreign travel by Czechs was then one with canned, beer and permanent wort, etc. packed suitcase.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely interchangeable Czech Krone - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency free.
Our standard of living and this has also increased the averages, which took place in 1997 at another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips after 1997 through charter flights, thereby allowing flight flights to deal with quantities discounts which were incredibly approved in comparison to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had a foreign exchange-free movement with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post office" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand for the first direct charter flight in an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying each year in distant sunny countries; this year they fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
