UNAM asphalt prevents loopholes
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM develop modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
It would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 holes if the rainy season in the Metropolitana del Valle de México (city of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, said that if the installation and maintenance of the asphalt dam are suitable, the number of holes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his presentation "Technical eye holes", which he considered to be chemistry on the occasion of the International Year, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which shows greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the roadblock and to avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heavy part of the oil - is a carbon hydrogen connection, from which some have a high molecular weight - the asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic zelastic behaviour.
The zelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180°C as a liquid, at 120°C it is very smooth and at almost 50°C, while at very low temperatures it is broken.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not the same, but one day it changes depending on weather conditions and temperature changes," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City were mostly a flexible road block consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three asphalt contained.
Among the top layers is a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt-based and then solidified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer was built in asphalt.
If the vehicles are moving on and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the roadblock.
"If it were a modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
"About the wear layer", he said, "will be a final layer, the so-called wear layer consisting of small stones, i.e. sand, which was also built in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
Those who receive and distribute most of the forces of this road block also need a suitable thickness and the material from which it consists must be maintained.
